For metrics, we can't (and don't need to) estimate the exact time each mapper takes. We only estimate the relative load among different mappers, which hopefully is proportional to their running times. So I've added the min estimated load and max estimated load of all mappers to the state, so that MetricReport reporter can report it to MetricReport which can then be compared against the actual mapper running time.

Currently when copy a file to late folder it always adds a component, if a file is first copied to hourly-late then to daily-late, it will add two components, making file names in the late folder inconsistent and hard to process. One option is to write a FilenameFormat for late data that does the following:
(1) It should enclose the original FilenameFormat class.
(2) If the file name doesn't exist in the late folder, do not rename.
(3) If it does exist, add a component "late[number]".
(4) `getRecordCount()` should remove all "late[number]" components, then call `getRecordCount()` of the enclose `FilenameFormat` instance.

stats I could find in a quick search), java 8 adoption was at 20% according
to https://plumbr.eu/blog/java/java-version-statistics-2015-edition
Given that gobblin is open source, I think we should wait until there is
further adoption of java 8 before migrating.

It seems as if a converter can only set properties in a task state if there is only 1 branch in the fork operator. Otherwise each branch gets its own copy of the task state, and properties set on the copies will not be persistent. Correct? We may need to rethink a way of getting metadata out of converters. It seems weird to say that properties set in a converter are persistent to the original task state only if there is 1 branch in the fork operator.
